The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative- Mr. Shawn Shoemaker.  The noted bolts were secured tool tight and the car released for transportation.    NARRI: 5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90  Cause Code: 224

Our driver was unloading the CTMV at consignee location and the product transfer hose burst near the connection to the CTMV pump. The driver shut down the process immediately to stop the release.     Our driver observed a 1" crack in the hose positioned at approximately 2 inches from the hose connector.          Event # 62136

Delivery driver utilized 2 hoses to make connection from trailer compartment to UST. Driver hooked up the hose connection to the fitting at the storage tank, then hooked up hose to the trailer compartment. Opened internal value, stayed with the delivery while flow of product was happening. Upon seeing the hose connection come off the fitting at the storage tank, driver immediately closed the internal valve to trailer. The driver notified 911 and both he and the store personnel immediately stopped all traffic in area and began cleanup while awaiting emergency assistance.    Review of the veeter root system information reflects that the product began flow at 12:55pm and stopped at 1:05pm with an increase of 35 gallons. This information is helpful in supporting the driver statement that the connections were made to both the storage tank and trailer compartment before opening the internal valve for flow.
column169: An unannounced observation was conducted on the driver for a delivery 3 weeks prior and all aspects of delivery was proper. Inspection of the delivery hose and connectors was done to ensure that they were at standards. At this point it appears that driver error was made either when the camlocks on the fittings were not locked in or that a gasket had fallen out of the fitting before connection. Driver has reviewed again the importance of verifying that connection are secured before starting the delivery flow.

column168: TCIX 70021 was reported leaking product from the manway area by PTRA train crews working in American Yard on 10/5/16 at approximately 1040 hours. Slick Response Services was notified to respond to the scene. Slick reported that there was a torn gasket and several loose bolts on the manway and a missing gasket on the pressure relief device both causing product to leak down the sides of the tank car.  Slick Response installed new gaskets on the manway and PRV and secured both devices and installed new seals. Approximately 2 gallons of product leaked from the car. There were a few spots on the ground that were treated with a environmentally safe microbug solution. The tank car sides were pressure washed with a microbug solution to remove the product. The scene was cleared at approximately 1330 hours.
column169: The consignee, Mercuria Energy Trading, was notified of the issue and approved the response. It is our understanding that they have or will notify Tesoro Refining of the issues with the tank car.

column168: The trailer was being dropped off at the Veolia facility located in Henderson, Co when the driver noticed a leak at the back of the trailer. The Veolia Facility Manager & EHS prepared a health and safety plan, donned proper PPE and opened the trailer doors to investigate the leak. The container was found between larger containers (55gals) sideways with a loose bung. The container was adjusted, the spill was cleaned up and the clean up material was disposed of properly. The container was weighed to measure the amount of hazardous material that spilled. The container was manifested at 40lbs, after the spill the container weighed 26lbs. Calculations were made to see if the spill was RQ and was determined it wasn't.

column168: At 0130 hours on 10/10/2016 I John Vergis, Environmental Officer for the Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway, was called by the WLE Brewster Yardmaster about tank car GAMX 9782 that was reported leaking by the midnight car inspector.  When I arrived, I saw that the protective housing had ice formed on it.  When I investigated, I found that the liquid valve on the B end of the car was leaking at the plug.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I then tightened the valve plug that was found to be only hand tight.  I removed old seal 0239952 from the protective housing lid and installed new seal 971777. I then released the car for service.

column168: On October 2, 2016 at 16:53 hours, personnel at CSXT discovered TILX 400753, a loaded UN 2187, Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid tank car to have released product from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Praxair, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2016-10-02-00038. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, the Schererville, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the pressure regulator was not working properly causing the car to continuously release carbon dioxide.  As a preventative measure the pressure to the car was reduced by releasing product to the car to a point of 180 psi.      A HAZMATHOLD was placed on TILX 400753 and will require an OTMA to continue in transportation to the consignee to be unloaded.    Cause Code: 422 at 2 points

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE DHL SERVICE CENTER AT 151 ZACHARY ROAD, MANCHESTER NH AT 0941 EST ON 10/05/2016. IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE FREIGHT CONTAINER AND AN OUTSIDE SPILL RESPONDER WAS CONTACTED FOR CLEAN UP AND PLACEMENT IN SALVAGE PACKAGING. A SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM SHIPPER.                                                                                                                                                                                  THE SHIPPER PROVIDED AN SDS THAT IDENTIFIED THE CONTENTS AS ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS LIQUID NOS, UN3082, CLASS 9, PG III. IT WAS COMPRISED OF ONE BOX, CONTAINING 4 X I GALLON PLASTIC INNER CONTAINERS. THE INNER CONTAINERS HAD SMALL CRACKS IN THE SEAMS AND THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM THEM. TOTAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOSS WAS ESTIMATED TO BE 2 GALLONS.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT TENDERED TO DHL EXPRESS AS DANGEROUS GOODS. IATA SPECIAL PROVISION A197 STATES THE FOLLOWING: THESE SUBSTANCES, WHEN TRANSPORTED IN SINGLE OR COMBINATION PACKAGING’S CONTAINING A NET QUANTITY PER SINGLE OR INNER PACKAGING OF 5 L OR LESS FOR LIQUIDS OR HAVING A NET MASS OF 5 KG OR LESS FOR SOLIDS, ARE NOT SUBJECT TO ANY OTHER PROVISIONS OF THESE REGULATIONS PROVIDED THE PACKAGING’S MEET THE GENERAL PROVISIONS OF 5.0.2.4.1,5.0.2.6.1.1 AND 5.0.2.8.                                                                                                                                                                                                               TRANSPORTATION VIA AIR WAS CONFIRMED.

column168: Our driver was delivering one IBC of hydrofluorosilicic acid, 23% solution at the City of Dayton water treatment facility using an electric pallet jack and the liftgate on the back of the semi-trailer.  When our driver reached the back of the trailer, the pallet jack slid off the liftgate causing the IBC to fall off and land on its top.  The impact of hitting the ground caused the side of the IBC to split open and it entire contents to drain out.  The contents of the IBC ran out on the paved driveway and into a rock lined drainage ditch alongside of the driveway.  The City of Dayton notified the fire department of the spill, they responded with their hazmat team.  The spill was neutralized using lime and inert materials.  We brought in a remediation contractor to cleanup the spill and restore the site to its original condition.
column169: Further training to prevent incidents of this nature include the following,  1. Driver retraining on the use of electric pallet jacks,  2. Retraining on the daily inspection of electric pallet jacks,  3. Retraining on the use of a truck mounted liftgate,  4. Retraining on the proper unloading procedures.

column168: UNIVAR DRIVER AND CUSTOMER RECEIVE FILLED OUT THE NECESSARY PAPERWORK FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER INTO CUSTOMERS TANK WHICH INCLUDED VERIFICATION OF BULK HOOK UP TO PROPER FITTINGS FOR THE PROPER TANK.     THE PRODUCT TRANSFER COMMENCED AND THE DRIVER WALKED THE PRODUCT HOSE TO CONNECTION VERIFYING ALL WAS OKAY. AFTER A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME DURING THIS VERIFICATION PROCESS THE DRIVER NOTICED THEY HAD HOOKED TO THE WRONG TANK. HE STOPPED THE TRANSFER INTO THE WRONG TANK AT THAT TIME.     SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS TRANSFERRED INTO FERRIC CHLORIDE TANK #2 RATHER THAN SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANK #2.     5 INDIVIDUALS WERE DRIVEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED. THEY WERE DRIVEN BY THE CUSTOMERS SUPERINTENDENT.
column169: THIS INCIDENT WILL BE PRESENTED AT THE NEXT TRAINING AT THE FACILITY TO REMIND ALL THE IMPORTANCE OF HOOKING TO THE CORRECT TANK AND DOUBLE CHECKING BEFORE TRANSFERRING PRODUCT.     PICTURES OF THE HOOK AT MWRA WILL BE PRESENTED AND REVIEWED, ASKING DRIVERS TO ADVISE THEIR SUPERVISOR OF ANY FACILITY THAT MAY HAVE CONFUSING BULK TRANSFER HOOK UP LOCATIONS, SO RECOMMENDATIONS CAN BE MADE TO MAKE CHANGES.

column168: On October 20, 2016, R & L Carriers (HST Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1263, Milamar X, 3, III (PRO#459749646) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were loading a trailer (OA3010) when terminal personnel discovered 1-350 gallon metal tote to be leaking. The caller indicated that the valve appeared to be knocked off. Terminal personnel put the cap on the valve back on prior to notification. The caller reported that the tote is still leaking. Approximately 10 gallons of product has been released to the trailer floor and concrete beneath. Contractor indicated that approximately 5 gallons was lost. Approximately 2 gallons of material was released to the area beneath the trailer. Contractor is using absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor indicated that during the loading process, terminal personnel knocked the cap off the valve causing the valve to open. Contractor has closed the valve and will conduct a "slosh" test to ensure that the tote is secure. Contractor indicated that there area outside of the trailer is 8' x 12'. Contractor has finished cleanup activities. Contractor has generated 1-55 gallon steel drum of impacted absorbents for waste.

column168: On October 05, 2016, terminal personnel discovered that a 330-gallon poly tote of the UN1760, 8, PG III Corrosive liquid "activator AX" had a loose cap that came off during transit causing approximately 5-gallons to release. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing absorbents and a soda ash solution. All impacted absorbents and debris were swept up and containerized into (3) 55-gallon poly drums which were staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage. The cap of the tote was placed back on and tightened and was also staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Broken Component or Device
column168: Responded to odor report in yard. Upon inspection I found that both liquid valves, the vapor valve, and the sample valve were all in the open position.  All 4 valves had plugs that were less than tool tight and they were leaking vapor.  MULTIPLE 1  Responded to odor report. Upon inspection I found the vapor valve was in the open position and the plug was less than tool tight.  MULTIPLE 2  Responded to report of odor. Upon inspection I found that the A end liquid valve and the vapor valve were both in the open position.  The plugs were loose allowing vapor to release by the threads.  MULTIPLE 3  Responded to report of odor.  Upon inspection I found the A end liquid valve was open and plug less than tool tight.  The sample valve was open and the plug threads were damaged, plug could not be placed.  MULTIPLE 4  Responded to report of an odor. Upon inspection I found the vapor valve was open and the plug less than tool tight.  MULTIPLE 5  Responded to odor report. Upon tank car inspection I found the B end liquid valve was frozen over.  After inspecting the valve I found that the packing nut was loose and it was releasing liquid which had frozen when leaving the car.  I tightened the nut and the release stopped.  After the it melted away I found that the plug as well as the plugs on the other valves were less than tool tight. I tightened the plug and replaced the security seal.
column169: Closed all valves, tightened all plugs.

column168: On 10/24/2016, at the R&L Carriers in San Antonio, TX, a 55 gallon poly drum of UN3266 ZEP SF 4086 was punctured by a fork lift blade while unloading a trailer. The damaged drum released approximately 20 gallons of material to the trailer floor and parking lot.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to clean the release.  The released material was neutralized and cleaned with granular absorbents.  All absorbents were collected into 55 gallon poly drums for disposal.  The damaged 55 gallon poly drum was overpacked into a 95 gallon poly over pack drum.  The over pack was labeled with all applicable shipping information and staged on site for R&L personnel to manage. All waste was taken by the contractor for disposal.

column168: ON 10-18-2016 AT 0515 HOURS, I WAS ADVISED OF A TANK CAR POSSIBLY RELEASING VAPORS AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD YARD IN RIVERDALE, IL. IHB OPERATIONS CENTER ADVISED CAR NUMBER GATX 95590 ON TRACK BC31 CONTAINING A FULL LOAD OF HYDROGEN SULFIDE SODIUM UN3289 PG II WAS REPORTED TO BE RELEASING VAPORS AFTER AN IHB CREW OF 3 MEMBERS WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AFTER REPORTEDLY INHALING THESE VAPORS. AT THIS TIME THE IHB BLUE ISLAND EAST YARD WAS SHUT DOWN UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE.     UPON ARRIVAL MYSELF (BRYAN FULLER, MANAGER OF HAZMAT OF IHB) AND CONNOR SCHAEFFER OF SUNPRO SERVICES HEADED DOWN TRACK 30 EQUIPPED WITH AIR MONITORS. UPON ARRIVE AT THE CAR THE AIR MONITORS WERE READING ZERO. AFTER CLIMBING THE CAR AND INSPECTING THE EQUIPMENT WE FOUND NO ISSUES AND THE MONITORS WERE STILL READING ZERO. WHEN INSPECTING HT MANWAY IT APPEARED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS NOT APPLIED PROPERLY. AFTER DISMOUNTING THE CAR AND DONNING SCBA'S MYSELF AND MR. SCHAEFFER OPENED UP THE MANWAY AND FOUND A DEFECTIVE AND IMPROPERLY APPLIED MAYWAY GASKET. TO MAKE SURE THE METERS WERE WORKING PROPERLY WE PLACED THE METER OVER THE OPENED MAYWAY AND THE METERS PROPERLY DETECTED THE PRODUCT. THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE MANWAY WAS SEALED BACK UP WITH NO ISSUES. THE RAILCAR WAS SHIPPED FROM SAFETY-KLEEN OUT OF EAST CHICAGO, IN.
column169: SPOKE WITH GREG MARINO OF CLEAN HARBORS (OWNER OF SAFETY-KLEEN) AND ADVISED THEY USE PROPER PRE SHIPMENT INSPECTIONS IN ORDER TO PREVENT NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES.     NRC REPORT # 1161844  ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT REPORT # H2016-0958.

column168: AT 1231 HOURS ON OCTOBER 8, 2016 IT WAS REPORTED THAT EMPTY PROPANE CAR PLMX 137670 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) RAIL YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, IL. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE. UPON INVESTIGATION, THE RESPONDER DETERMINED THAT BOTH LIQUID LINES WERE NOT CLOSED PROPERLY AND BOTH PLUGS WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT. THE RESPONDER CLOSED BOTH VALVES ON THE LIQUID LINES AND TIGHTENED THE PLUGS TOOL TIGHT. THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.     FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT (I.E. ONE CAR LOAD), THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALVE.

ASP Driver, Ben Marshall, had completed the anhydrous ammonia fill on Musashi's tank. The safety (B.A.S.E.) system on the cargo tank was shut down, thus all valves (i.e. internal, snappy joe, etc.) were closed. The driver did not properly disconnect the 1" X 100' delivery hose prior to pulling away, which resulted in an unsafe line break (at the customer's tank connection), a release of anhydrous ammonia (21 lbs./vaporization is immediate so actual duration of release is unknown), and property damage to both the customer's and Airgas' equipment. The leak was mitigated by safety valves on both ends of the system (excess flow valve shut on customer's fill connection/internal and snappy joe valves on Airgas' discharge line shut). The driver tested all connections where stress was applied as a result of the pull-away, and no leaks were present. No authorities were called to the site, and Musashi returned to normal operation after a 1 hr. evacuation of approximately 100-500 employees. The driver was directed to leave the site shortly thereafter by area manager, Michael Jones.
column169: Established Airgas SOP A-03 specifically states that all delivery hoses are to be disconnected prior to pulling away. No recommendations will be made regarding the content of that particular SOP.     Airgas has recommended that a brake interlock system be installed on this cargo tank, such that if a hose is extended off of its reel, all air will be lost to the trailer, which will set/lock the brakes and prevent such occurrence in the future.     Airgas has also determined that the driver be disciplined, and re-trained on the established Airgas SOP A-03 thereafter.

On October 13, 2016 during loading operations, terminal personnel accidentally punctured a (1) 330-gallon poly tote containing UN3109 Organic Peroixde "Type F Peroxyacetic Acid Microtox Ultra", during a forklift accident. Approximately 50-gallons released to the concrete dock floor. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing granular absorbents and soda ash. All impacted absorbents and debris were containerized into a (6) 55-gallon poly drums and staged onsite for the terminal personnel to manage. The remaining salvaged material in the damaged tote was transferred into a new (1) 330-gallon poly tote which was also staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

column168: THE IRREG SORTER ACROSS FROM DOOR 202 IN THE BLUE WAS SLIDING A HAZMAT PACKAGE ACROSS THE ROLLERS WHEN HE DISCOVERED IT WAS LEAKING. HE NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I TESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID   FOUND IT TO BE APPROX 1. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID. I RETESTED THE PH FOUND IT TO BE APPROX 6. I THEN USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. I PUT A BIT MORE ABSORBANT DOWN   SWEPT IT UP TO ENSURE ALL RESIDUE WAS GONE. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT ONE OF THE CAPS HAD COME OFF THAT THE REMAINING BOTTLES HAD BEEN SOILED BY THE PRODUCT.
column169: USE TAPE, STICKERS OR CUSHIONING TO HELP KEEP CAPS SECURELY IN PLACE.

column168: he onsite Coca Cola chemist stated that the personnel was adding a type of UN1908 Chlorite Solution to a (1) 330-gallon metal tote. They were adding the solution by hand and accidentally poured the substance to fast which caused the solution of off gas. The personnel then moved the tote outside and called the fire department. The fire department added water to the tote which reacted. The reaction caused the metal tote to explode causing the personnel hand to blow off.
column169: Proper loading of the material and a proper response from the fire department would have prevented the release.

column168: AT 0600 HRS. BPRR TRAIN BT01 WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON THE MAIN LINE WHEN THEY PASSED A CUT OF LOADED PROPANE CARS SECURED ON THE RUNNER SOUTH TRACK. CREW REPORTED OVER THE RADIO TO THE YARDMASTER THEY THOUGHT THEY SMELLED A PROPANE ODOR COMING FROM ONE OF THE LOADED CARS LOCATED ON THE RUNNER SOUTH TRACK. A CAR INSPECTOR, WHO WAS IN THE VICINITY, OVERHEAD THE CONVERSATION AND HEADED OVER TO CHECK THE CARS FOR ANY VISUAL LEAKS OR PROBLEMS. UPON INSPECTION, THE CAR INSPECTOR FOUND AN ODOR EMITTING FROM THE MANWAY DOME COVER OF CAR PLMX 137331.     MARKWEST ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 0800 HRS. AND FOUND THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A FAULTY B-END LIQUID VALVE AND PLUG. THE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE, THE LOOSE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED.     SPECIALIZED PROFESSIONAL SERVICES, INC. (SPSI) ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 0810 HRS. AFTER THE CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED. THE ALL CLEAR WAS GIVEN AT 0820 HRS.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was parked in the ten day storage yard of the intermediate truck transfer facility. Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that 3 of the 8 manway cover swing bolts were less than tool tight. Contractor personnel opened the manway, inspected the manway gasket, and properly secured all manway cover bolts. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. column168: On 10/18/2016 at 2010 hours, CSX Transportation personnel reported a significant odor present near tank car GATX 18347. CSX Transportation made all necessary regulatory and customer notifications, isolated the car from employees, and contracted with Specialized Professional Services, Inc (SPSI) of Washington, PA to respond. Upon arrival SPSI found approximately 2-3 ounces of liquid product adjacent to the manway nozzle / cover interface. All manway cover bolts were found secured to necessary tool-tightness, however there was a continued audible noise consistent with a vapor release near the manway cover hand-hold. SPSI applied a wrench to the manway cover bolts, secured each bolt one additional quarter-turn, and successfully stopped the release.

column168: The semi truck was involved in an auto accident.  It left the roadway and laid over on its side.  The local fire department and hazardous response team were on scene to assess and contain the spill.      There was a diesel release from the fuel tanks and the cargo consisting of paint/solvents was also leaking.  The leak was diverted to the soil shoulder by the local Fire department.  Approximately 500 gallons of paint/solvent and 200 gallons of fuel were released in the rural area.    A hazardous material company was called in to remove the leaking drums and cans and clean up the contaminated soil impacted from the release.     The load consisted of 36 55 gallon drums of solvent and 200 1 gallon cans of paint/solvent.     A number of the drums and cans were crushed and leaking as a result of being thrown around in the crash.     The environmental company remediated the effected soil and removed the leaking containers from the area.  The waste was disposed of at an eligible disposal facility.
column169: The result of a spill was as a result an accident.  Under normal shipping conditions the containers used to ship the material are adequate.

column168: XNG NOTIFIED AT 0145 THEY HAD A TRAILER WITH UNDETERMINED LEAK POINT. FIELD ENGINEER ARRIVED ON SITE AT 0335 AS WELL AS PLYMOUTH FIRE DEPARTMENT, INSPECTED TRAILER XT-142 (CYLINDERS @ 300 PSIG) FOR GENERAL CONDITION AND POINT OF LEAK. THE SMELL OF ODORANT WAS NOTICEABLE IN THE AREA OF THE TRAILER. ENGINEER INVESTIGATED THE LEAK DISCOVERED THE LEAKAGE COMING FROM THE "NH VALVE" ACTUATORS. LEAK POINTS WERE AT THE O-RINGS OF THE ACTUATOR TRAVEL LIMIT ADJUSTMENT SCREWS IN THE BODY OF THE "NH MOD" ACTUATORS. THE SUPPLY GAS FOR THIS IS AT 100 PSIG, WHICH IS REGULATED DOWN FROM THE CYLINDER PRESSURE. THE AMOUNT OF RELEASED WAS VERY SMALL. THE ENGINEER TIGHTENED ALL ADJUSTMENT SCREWS MITIGATING ANY AND ALL LEAKAGE. THE ENGINEER WALKED AROUND THE TRAILER AGAIN WITH FIRE CHIEF AND CONFIRMED THERE WERE NO OTHER LEAKS.
column169: TERMINAL OPERATORS INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT NH ACTUATOR VALVES ON TRAILERS PRIOR TO DISPATCH TO ENSURE SET SCREWS ON THE VALVES WERE TIGHTENED PREVENTING ANY LEAKAGE AT THE O-RINGS.

column25: TRADEBE TREATMENT AND RECYCLING OF TENNESSEE, LLC
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A LEAK FROM THE TRAILER WHILE STOPPED AT THE FLYING J TRUCK STOP. INDIANA SPILL RESPONSE, LLC (ISR) OF SHELBYVILLE, IN WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ISR RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE AREA. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE ASPHALT UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER. ISR DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID ON THE IMPACTED ASPHALT AND INSIDE THE TRAILER. ISR INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED ONE (1) LEAKING 330-GALLON PLASTIC TOTE. AN ESTIMATED 40 GALLONS WERE RELEASED. THE MATERIAL FROM THE LEAKING TOTE WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A NEW TOTE. ISR RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO THREE (3) 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THE WASTE WAS LEFT ON THE TRAILER FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, TRADEBE TRANSPORTATION, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: It was reported that the driver of a Santmyer Oil (SOCI Petroleum) tanker overfilled the underground storage tank with UN1203 gasoline. Approximately 100 gallons of material were released onto the asphalt parking area, into soils and into a storm drain. A nearby contractor responded to flush the sewer line and clean the impacted area.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: It was reported that (1) 275 gallon poly tote containing UN3266 was crushed by other freight and was discovered with a damaged cap. Approximately 1 gallon of material was released inside the trailer. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. A nearby contractor responded and replaced the damaged cap.

One 5 gallon poly pail containing UN1760 Corrosive Liquid was discovered damaged on the dock releasing approximately 5 gallons of material. A contractor responded to perform cleanup operations. The damaged pail was placed into a drum along with the impacted waste debris. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.
column198: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column168: On October 24, 2016, The caller stated that while at a costumers location (Johnsonville Sausage-6928 North Johnsonville Way, Sheboygan Falls WI) during unloading operations, the driver (Tim Brockway 920-602-2315) noticed that a (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing UN3264 Hydrochloric Acid "EnviroClean 110" damaged due to not being blocked and braced. Approximately 20-gallons released to the trailer floor and and soil/gravel underlying parking lot. The contractor container, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing absorbents and soda ash solution. All impacted absorbents and debris were containerized into a (1) 55-gallon poly drum which was transported back to the XPO terminal for the personnel to manage.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: CALLED TO THE PD-11 OUTBOUND FOR A WET PACKAGE ON THE BELT. PACKAGE WAS MARKED WITH A CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL AND UPS SHIPPING PAPERS. WEARING PROPER PPE AND FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND PROPER RESPONSE SHEET THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A LINED SPILL TUB ALONG WITH ANY DEBRIS AND MATERIAL USED TO CLEAN SPILL. PACKAGE WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP TO BE PROCESSED. AFTER OPENING THE PACKAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A CORNER ON ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. On October 17, 2016 a Marathon Pipe Line owned and operated vacuum truck carrying petroleum crude oil was involved in a one vehicle roll-over accident in Wyoming.  Immediate notification under 49 CFR 171.5 was provided to NRC based on the driver being admitted to a hospital.  After further review, immediate notification was not required s the accident was a direct result of the hazardous material but rather from the truck rollover and damage to the truck cabin.  Additionally, a written report under 49 CFR 171.6 would not have been required based on meeting the reporting exceptions under 49 CFR 171.16(d)(2)(iii)-(iv) for a release less than 5.2 gallons.  While the incident would not have met the immediate reporting requirements, a written report is therefore required.  No release occurred from the tank itself (lading system).  An amount less than one gallon of crude oil was released from a one foot 3" rubber "muffler" hose located between the tank muffler and scrubber tank.  This hose can collect crude oil mist residues during operation of the tanker truck and is capped with a camlock cap.  It is drained as necessary and would not allow a release from the tank.  An estimated 4 gallons of diesel fuel was also released from the trucks saddle tank which is not subject to reporting.  The spilled crude oil and diesel contaminated soil was picked up for proper disposal.  The tanker truck was removed from the site and taken to our Chatham Station south of Worland, WY.  NOTES: The "police" report number is for Wyoming Highway Patrol.  Response cost includes cost to haul off damaged truck as well as to empty the tank to recover crude oil.
column169: Marathon Pipe Line is in the process of conducting a TapRoot investigation to better understand the cause and provide recommendations to prevent recurrence.  This incident was a one vehicle roll-over accident and not the direct result of hazardous material.

column168: Trailer 511155 started venting off slowly at customer site while the driver was unloading to the tank. The driver opened the vapor blow off to help drop the tank pressure. column168: THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT HE SAW A "POOF OF SMOKE FROM THE DOME LID WHILE TRAVELING TO THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION BUT INDICATED THAT HE ASSUMED IT WAS VENTING. HE THEN SAW A SECOND "POOF FROM THE DRAIN TUBE AREA ON THE TANKER AND STOPPED TO INSPECT THE TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 3 MILES FROM THE DELIVERY LOCATION AND DID NOT SEE ANY LEAKAGE. UPON ARRIVAL, ON SITE PERSONNEL INFORMED THE DRIVER THAT THE TANKER WAS LEAKING AND IT WAS NOTED THAT MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE DOME LID AND POOLED IN THE DOME LID BOX. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE GASKET ON THE DOME LID WAS CUT ON ONE EDGE WHICH WAS A RESULT OF THE GASKET GETTING PINCHED AS THE DOME LID WAS CLOSED BY THE SHIPPER. IT IS ASSUMED THAT THE LEAK BEGAN AT THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AND LASTED THE DURATION OF THE TRIP OF 1.5 HOURS. THE TEAR IN THE GASKET WAS ABOUT 0.5 INCH BY 3 INCHES AND IT WAS REPLACED. QC EVENT #62112

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On October 20, 2016 at 0240 hours, personnel at CSXT Barr Yard discovered CBTX 718618, a loaded UN 1268, Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. tank car to have released product from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, WRB Refining LLC was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2016-10-20-00011. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, the Schererville, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection Sunpro observed two (2) loose manway swing bolts and a compromised manway gasket. SUNPRO installed a new manway gasket, closed the manway, tightened each swing bolt, and secured the manway shut with seal #419861.
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On October 26, 2016 at 0915 ET, (6) 55-gallon poly drums and (3) 330-gallon steel totes arrived with a release of approximately 2 ounces released in total from all three totes and six drums. The release came from the pressure relief valve on all containers and was later confirmed by the shipper that they were too loose and needed to be properly tightened down with tools. A cleanup contractor was dispatched and tightened all valves down properly. The containers were wiped down to remove any residual product. All generated waste was taken by the contractor for proper disposal.

On October 20, 2016, LARS was advised of a leaking unit at destination San Bernardino IBU. YRC Chemical Helpline was contacted for assistance due to the trailer actively leaking. Patriot Environmental was dispatched to remediate the leak at our facility. The leak material was determined to be  gallon loss of FAST CURE LAMINATING RESIN, HAZARD CLASS 3, UN1866, shipping from origin facility Advanced Coatings Company, Westminster, MA enroute to Dura Technologies, Bloomington, CA. The leak material originated from two (2) defective 55 gallon drums with cracks on the bottom of the drums found within the load. The two (2) drums were over packed and the leak material remediated within the trailer. Half of the load was split into RDWY 130855; both trailers released for outgate from San Bernardino IBU.
column169: Additional care in handling and packaging drums into trailers to avoid drum damage and product loss.

column168: During a routine load check, a driver of a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste noticed a small amount of liquid leaking from the rear door of the trailer.  Upon opening the door, it was found that a drum had collapsed the pallet causing it to lean onto another drum, popping the lid and causing some liquid to leak.  A response crew was summoned and upon arrival donned the appropriate personal protective equipment.  The drum was over-packed into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent pads and cleaning compound used to clean the trailer floor and ground.  The load then continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The origin location was notified that the load was not properly blocked in and the pallet was in bad shape.  The location will retrain the responsibility in proper load securement.

column168: A sea container with hazardous waste was received at the Veolia Facility located in Azusa California on October 20, 2016. While unloading the sea container, a 30 gallon open top drum was found with the lid blown off the top of drum. Whatever reaction took place must have happened while the container was on the ship at sea.  There was no evidence that any liquid or solid hazardous waste was release from the sea container. Furthermore, no liquid or solid residue was seen outside the drum. Whatever reaction took place utilized all the waste involved in the reaction. The vermiculite absorbent material was blown from the drum as well. There were a total of 9 smaller containers (ranging from pint to gallon) inside the 30 gallon drum. The other smaller inner containers were all constructed of metal. Some of the small containers were also blown out of the drum but none of the smaller containers were compromised.     No liquids were released from the drum. There was a stain left on the wall of the container from the reaction. The initial clean-up involved sweeping up all of the vermiculite absorbent and placing it back in the drum as well as any small containers blown from the drum.  All of the smaller containers were eventually consolidated into other containers for shipment off-site.
column169: It is unknown what caused the material in the drum to react.  The incident was reviewed with the shipper.  Veolia recommended better inventory control of the number and types of wastes are going into the packaging. Better labels on all inner containers.

column168: On October 26, 2016, during unloading operations, they discovered a (2) 2.5-gallon poly pjugs containing a pail of UN1760 Corrosive Liquid "Phosphoric Acid Leracid KMS 10" leaking from the caps due to what appears to be a manufacturing defect. Both caps were tightened but still leaked. Approximately 3-cups released to the trailer floor in trailer #OA3400. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing granular absorbents and soda ash. All impacted absorbents and debris were over-packed into a (1) 5-gallon poly pail. The two damaged pails were over-packed and staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Upon receipt inspection it appeared that the box had been dented and the internal contents were rattling inside the box.  An Ecology Services radiological technician took smear samples on the box and the floor of the office trailer where Federal Express delivered the package.  The smears were counted and it was determined that the box had removable contamination at 5,800 dpm/100cm2 and the office floor was 1,200 dpm/100cm2.  The package was placed in the licensed warehouse in an area designated for radioactive contamination.  The office floor was decontaminated.  The tritium exit signs were removed from the package, decontaminated, and prepared for shipment to a recycle/disposal facility.
column169: Shipper was notified and instructed to use better and more cushioning material (more bubble wrap) to prevent movement and shock damage to tritium exit signs during transport.

column168: On 10/24/16, ODOT Hazmat Inspector Christopher Kuenzi inspected the DPRX 257252.  The FRA inspection report submitted by Mr. Kuenzi states:    "Inspection of this tank car last containing UN1267 Petroleum Crude Oil found a definite odor of product from the area of the protective housing on top the car and the vacuum relief valve had some product on the valve body and was making a slight noise. I reported this issue to BNSF mechanical foreman John Ohlman at the time of  my inspection. I did not replace the security seal that I removed from the protective housing since BNSF personnel will need to perform repairs inside the protective housing."  BNSF Hazmat Team members isolated the car from the train and inspected the car.  The VRV was removed from the pressure plate and a blind flange was installed in place to secure the leak.  The VRV was fastened to a valve for the car owner/shop to conduct additional inspection and testing on the defective valve.  An OTMA was obtained by PBF Energy for the trip to shop for repairs.  Estimated release volumes are only estimates based upon information provided by the field.
column169: The shipper should ensure that all appliances are in conformance with the tank car specification and leak free prior to release.  The shipper has been notified for follow up.

column168: TILX191835 was noted by an inspector with the Arizona Corporation Commission as producing an ethanol odor. Upon investigation by BNSF HazMat responders, the odor was emitting from the manway area. The manway bolts were tool tight upon inspection as well.  The manway lid was opened up to find a gasket in the lid that was elongated and causing the gasket to not seal properly.  The gasket was replaced with a new manway nozzle gasket and the lid secured with the swing bolts tool tight.
column169: Shipper needs to confirm that seals and gaskets are intact and not leaking product, whether liquid or vapor.  This process needs to occur on both loaded and residue cars prior to shipping to prevent a hazardous material release.

column168: Tank car OLGX 29043 derailed and was punctured through the head end by the preceding car's knuckle. The UPRR and BNSF Hazmat Managers attempted to slow the rate of release using wood wedges and putty with partial success. The car released its contents for approximately 4 hours. The incident resulted in a total release of approximately 17,265 gallons.

column168: A TRUCK DRIVEN BY WILLIE TRUE FOR SPECIALIZED TRANSPORT OF WAVERLY, ILLINOIS, WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF DYED DIESEL FUEL TOTALING 7,564 GALLONS TO THE ILLINI FS LOADING RACK OFF ROUTE 45 NORTHWEST OF TUSCOLA, ILLINOIS. THE TRANSFER HOSE FAILED CAUSING THE DIESEL FUEL TO SPURT OUT. THE TRUCK DRIVER NOTICED THE PUMP WAS SOUNDING DIFFERENT, SO HE WENT TO CHECK IN BACK OF THE TRUCK AND FOUND THE RELEASE OCCURRING. HE WENT BACK TO THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AND SHUT THE PUMP OFF. DURATION RELEASE WAS 30 SECONDS TO ONE MINUTE LENGTH.     THE TRUCK WAS LATER UNLOADED. BY COMPARING THE READINGS FROM WHAT WAS LOADED IN THE TANKER AND WHAT WAS DELIVERED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS SPILLED. AS SOON AS THE SPILL HAPPENED, THE DRIVER STARTED SOAKING UP THE SPILLED FUEL ON THE GROUND WITH ABSORBENT PADS.     INITIALLY THE GROWMARK LOGISTICS DEPARTMENT WAS ALERTED THAT AROUND 15 GALLONS OF FUEL HAD SPILLED. ILLINI FS SAFETY & REGULATORY SUPERVISOR, PAL TITUS, WENT OUT TO THE SITE. SHE IDENTIFIED THERE WAS MORE FUEL SPILLED THAN WHAT WAS ORIGINALLY REPORTED, SO SHE MADE THE CALLS TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, THE IL EPA, AND TO THE DOUGLAS COUNTY LEPC. TITUS ALSO WENT BACK TO THE SAFETY OFFICE AND BROUGHT OUT MORE ABSORBENT PADS.     SPECIALIZED TRANSPORT HAS HIRED BODINE ENVIRONMENT BOB APLINGER, 217-519-3947 TO INSPECT THE SITE AND MITIGATE, IF WARRANTED.
column169: SUGGEST TO CARRIER TO INSPECT PRODUCT TRANSFER HOSE ON A REGULAR BASIS.
column198: Illini FS, division of GROWMARK, Inc.

column168: At approximately 4PM a Private Carriage driver was involved in a release of HCl while unloading at the Oxy Chlorine plant in Geismar, LA. The event occurred 5 minutes into the unloading process, when the end of the hose connected to the customer's connection partially separated from the body of the unloading hose. The driver responded immediately by closing the product valve with the remote shutdown switch. The incident resulted in the spill of approximately 15 gallons of HCl which was cleaned up by the Geismar Plant. No injuries were reported.
column169: Investigate hose failure.

column168: Once barge was off loaded we then pressurized the line to blow remaining product to tank.  During the first line blowdown while walking the line operator noticed a mist of Caustic coming from the flex joint.  He then immediately shut down the compressor.  After the pressure was off the line and safe to approach we noticed a failure in the rubber of the flex connection.  Approximately 1854 dry pound of NaOH (291 gal of 50%) leaked from the expansion joint into Mississippi river, there are no known or anticipated acute or chronic health risks associated with the release and there are no known exposed individuals.
column169: The following actions were implemented:    Take line out of service until failure mode determined-Complete  Replace failed flex joint with S.S. section - Completed 10/25/16  Conduct engeneering study and review the need of expansion joint on the line. In progress

column168: THE FUEL SOUTH EXPRESS TRANSPORT WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON STATE ROAD 87 IN THE RIGHT LANE. AS THE TRANSPORT APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF STATE ROAD 87 AND COLEY STATION ROAD, THE CHRYSLER VAN RAN THE STOP SIGN AND TRAVELED INTO THE PATH OF OUR VEHICLE. OUR TRANSPORT STRUCK THE LEFT FRONT OF THE CHRYSLER VAN. THE AREA OF IMPACT OCCURRED IN THE RIGHT SOUTHBOUND LANE OF STATE ROAD 87.  AFTER IMPACT, THE TRANSPORT TRAVELED ACROSS THE CENTER LINE AND THEN OVERTURNED ONTO ITS PASSENGER SIDE AND SLID DOWN THE ROADWAY. THE CAB OF THIS VEHICLE TRAVELED OFF THE ROAD AND ONTO THE EAST SHOULDER OF HIGHWAY 87 BEFORE OVERTURNING ONTO ITS DRIVER'S SIDE.  THE ACCIDENT AND SUBSEQUENT ROLLOVER OF THE MOVING TRANSPORT CAUSED HOLES TO BE CREATED IN THE TANKER SIDE AS IT SLID DOWN THE ROAD AT NORMAL HIGHWAY SPEEDS. THE RELEASE WAS SLOWED BY EFFORTS OF THE FIRST RESPONDENTS. FOAM WAS SPRAYED TO MINIMIZE PRODUCT VAPORS.    A SECOND TRANSPORT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE BY FUEL SOUTH EXPRESS AND ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER 4:00 A.M. THE SECOND TRANSPORT BEGAN TO PUMP THE REMAINING PRODUCT OFF WHILE WORKING WITH FIRST RESPONDENTS TO UPRIGHT THE DAMAGED UNIT. PRODUCT THAT LEAKED RAN TO A DRY HIGHWAY DITCH AND SOAKED DIRECTLY INTO THE SOIL. AFTER THE TRANSPORT WAS REMOVED, THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS OVER-EXCAVATED AND REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: THE TRANSPORT WAS TRAVELING IN THE CORRECT LANE (OUTSIDE LANE) AT THE POSTED SPEED AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. THE IMPACT CAUSED THE ROLLOVER OF THE TANK AND THE IMPACT AND FRICTION OF THE HIGHWAY CAUSED THE BREACH IN THE TANKER SIDEWALL. FUEL SOUTH EXPRESS IS UNABLE TO FORMULATE ANY RECOMMENDATIONS AT THIS TIME THAT WOULD PREVENT POTENTIAL FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

column168: FUEL OIL, 3" PRODUCT HOSE RUPTURED DURING OFF-LOADING TO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK. THE DELIVERY WAS A PUMP FED OFFPAD AND THERE WAS MINIMAL PRESSURE, THE HOSE EMPTIED ITS CONTENTS ON THE GROUND BEFORE THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO SHUT THE LOADING VALVE.    THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS 8 TO 10 SECONDS, AND THE SIZE OF THE HOSE RUPTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 TO 3 INCHES IN DIAMETER.     MITIGATING EFFORTS WERE IMMEDIATELY TAKEN, THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE FLOW OF PRODUCT, WITHIN 15 TO 20 SECONDS AND IMMEDIATELY PLACED SPEEDY DRY ABSORBENT AND ABSORBENT PADS DOWN AT THE SITE TO PREVENT THE SPREAD OF THE PRODUCT.
column169: INVESTIGATED THE POTENTIAL TO CHANGE THE DELIVERY HOSE WHEN DOING A PUMPED DELIVERY, FROM A 3" DIAMETER HOSE WITH A WORKING PRESSURE OF 65 PSI TO A HIGH PRESSURE 150 PSI DELIVERY HOSE.    CONDUCT ANNUAL HOSE PRESSURE TEST AT 1.5 TIMES THE WORKING PRESSURE. INVESTIGATE THE DESIGN OF THE HOSE CONNECTION AT THE DELIVERY SITE OT REDUCE THE POTENTIAL STRAIN ON THE HOSE.     FROM THIS POINT FORWARD, WE WILL BE USING AN PLICORD 2" EXTREME FLEX INDUSTRIAL PETROLEUM TRANSFER HOSE, WITH A WORKING PRESSURE OF 250 PSI, ALL PUMP OFF HOSES WILL TESTED ANNUALLY 1 1/2 TIMES THEIR WORKING PRESSURE (375 PSI)

column168: THE CARGO TANK TRUCK WAS HEADING WEST ON 270 BYPASS TURNING LEFT ONTO I-30 WESTBOUND ENTRANCE RAMP. IT WAS TRAVELING TOO FAST FOR THE TURN CAUSING IT TO ENTER INTO A ROLLOVER PATTERN. IT CONTINUED IN THE ROLLOVER PATTERN EXITING THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST IN THE DITCH AGAINST THE TREES FACING WEST ON THE DRIVERS SIDE. EMERGENCY WORKERS RESPONDED VERY QUICKLY TO ASSIST THE DRIVER IN EXITING THE VEHICLE AND CONTAINING A SMALL LEAK AROUND A DOME LID. THE WORKERS PLACED DOOMS AROUND THE LOWER SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK TO ABSORB ANY RUNOFF. THE DOME LID REMAINED CLOSED, HOWEVER THE SEAL AROUND THE LID ALLOWED DIESEL TO LEAK IN A SPRAY PATTERN APPROXIMATELY 5 INCHES WIDE. THE LEAK CONTINUED AS THE CARGO TANK WAS BEING RIGHTED FOR APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES. ONCE UPRIGHT, THE DIESEL WAS PUMPED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. AFTER THE WRECKAGE WAS REMOVED, AN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY IMMEDIATELY EXAMINED THE SPILL SITE AND DETERMINED THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO A SMALL AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 23 FEET WIDE BY 20 FEET LONG.
column169: IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TWO CONTRIBUTING FACTORS TO THIS ACCIDENT WERE SPEED AND THE DESIGN OF THE ROADWAY. THE ROADWAY IN THIS TURN IS BANKED TO THE OUTSIDE INSTEAD OF THE INSIDE REQUIRING A MUCH LOWER THAN NORMAL SPEED TO PREVENT A ROLLOVER.     AS OUR COMPANY MOVES FORWARD, WE ARE PLACING AN EVEN STRONGER EMPHASIS ON ROLLOVER TRAINING AND THE DANGERS OF SPEED AND CARGO TANKS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL

column168: ON THE MORNING OF OCTOBER 9, 2016, ACORD TRANSPORTATION INC. OWNER/OPERATOR GALE JUEL WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT THE CF INDUSTRIES PLANT LOCATED AT 1000 TERRA DRIVE IN WOODWARD, OK 73801. MR. JUEL WAS IN TRUCK #598 WAS PULLING TRAILER #7183.    DURING THE LOADING PROCESS AT APPROXIMATELY 8:45 AM. A PRESSURE SEAL WITHIN THE BLACKMER PUMP ON MR. JUEL'S TRAILER FAILED. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 215 LBS (ACCORDING TO CF INDUSTRIES PERSONNEL) OF PRODUCT (ANHYDROUS AMMONIA) WAS RELEASED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE LOADING PROCESS WAS HALTED IMMEDIATELY. THERE WAS NOT DAMAGE, INJURIES OR EVACUATION AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.     ONCE THE LOADING PROCESS WAS STOPPED, THE TRUCK/TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE LOADING AREA. THE SCHEDULED LOAD FOR MR. JUEL WAS CANCELLED THEREFORE, THERE ARE NOT SHIPPING PAPER/ DOCUMENTS AVAILABLE (BOL, TRIP SHEET, ETC)
column169: PRIOR TO BEING DISPATCHED FOR ANY OTHER LOAD, MR. JUEL WAS INSTRUCTED TO GET TRAILER 7183 INTO A REPAIR SHOP TO HAVE ALL THE NECESSARY COMPONENTS CORRECTED. MR. JUEL TOOK TRAILER 7183 TO HIGH GEAR REPAIR LOCATED AT 40684 S. COUNTY ROAD 206 IN WOODWARD, OK 73801.     WHILE AT HIGH GEAR REPAIR, NO COMPONENT WAS OVERLOOKED. ALTHOUGH IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A SEAL IS WHAT HAD FAILED DURING THE INCIDENT, MULTIPLE ITEMS WERE GONE OVER TO ENSURE THAT THE REMAINDER OF THE COMPONENTS WERE IN SAFE OPERABLE CONDITION. THESE ITEMS INCLUDED ALL SEALS, BEARING, O-RINGS AND END PLATES. ATTACHED WITH THIS REPORT IS A WORK ORDER FOR HIGH GEAR REPAIR DOCUMENTING THE REPAIRS.     ALTHOUGH IT IS UNDERSTANDABLE THAT OCCASIONALLY MECHANICAL FAILURES CAN OCCUR, WE WANT TO COMMUNICATE THAT PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE IS A TOP PRIORITY AT ACORD TRANSPORTATION. WE HAVE A VERY EXTENSIVE PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE PROGRAM THAT REQUIRES THAT EACH PIECE OF EQUIPMENT IS CONSISTENTLY, CONTINUOUSLY AND THOROUGHLY INSPECTED ON AN ONGOING BASIS TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE AND SAFE OPERATION.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE, CARGO TANK WAS OVERFILLED DURING THE LOADING OPERATION. MATERIAL CONTINUED TO FLOW INTO THE TRAILER AND OVERFLOWED INTO THE SPILL BOX. FROM THERE IT RAIN DOWN THE SPILL BOX HOSE AND WAS RELEASED INTO THE FACILITY LOADING CONTAINMENT PAD.     ABSORBENT PADS WERE APPLIED TO THE RELEASED MATERIAL BY THE DRIVER. STILL EMPLOYEES AND A CONTRACTOR CLEAN UP CREW ALREADY ON SITE MITIGATED THE RELEASE TO THE CONTAINMENT AND THE TRAILER SPILL BOX.
column169: THE DRIVER SHOULD REMAIN ON THE LOADING RACK OBSERVING THE LOADING DURING THE ENTIRE PROCESS AND TEST THE FACILITY PUMP SHUTDOWN SWITCH BEFORE REACHING TRAILER FILL POINT TO ENSURES ITS OPERATION. REVIEW CURRENT LOADING PROCEDURE AT TERMINAL AND DEVELOP ADDITIONAL SAFETY CONTROL OR MODIFY FOR LOADING AT CUSTOMERS LOCATION.

column168: ON OCTOBER 21, HARCROS DRIVER DELIVERED A BULK LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID SOLUTION TO CUSTOMER SITE, MGP, IN ATCHISON, KS, THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT MGP AND PREPARED FOR THE TRANSFER INTO AN ABOVE GROUND TANK. THE DRIVER CONNECTED THE TRANSFER HOSE TO THE RECEIVING VALVE THAT WAS UNLOCKED BY MGP AND THEN STARTED THE TRANSFER PROCESS. A FEW MINUTES LATER THE HARCROS DRIVER NOTICED A GREEN FOG COMING FROM THE TOP OF MGP’S SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE FLOW OF THE SULFURIC ACID FROM THE TANKER TRAILER BUT HAD TROUBLE BREATHING AND WAS OVERCOME BY THE FUMES AND HAD TO RETREAT AWAY FROM THE CLOUD OF GAS COMING OUT OF THE ABOVE GROUND TANK.   THE HARCROS DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO THE LOCAL EMERGENCY ROOM AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED WITHIN A FEW HOURS. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS EVACUATED MGP AND THE SURROUNDING AREA.   LATER THAT MORNING DOT, EPH, OSHA, PHMSA WERE ALL ON SITE AT MGP TO CONDUCT INVESTIGATIONS. KANSAS HIGHWAY PATROL EXAMINERS INSPECTED THE HARCROS TRACTOR AND TRAILER AND RELEASED IT FOLLOWING THEIR INSPECTION. REPORT IS ATTACHED.   INVESTIGATIONS AT MGP BY EPA AND OSHA ARE ONGOING AS OF DATE OF THIS SUBMITTAL.

column168: ON 10-11-16, DRIVER TRANSFERRED ULTRA GEL 950 FROM IBC TOTES INTO A TANKER ON WELL SITE. ONCE COMPLETED, THE DRIVER TRANSPORTED THE LOAD FROM ONE WELL SITE TO ANOTHER 25 MILES AWAY. WHILE EN ROUTE TO NEW LOCATION, THE DOG EARS SECURING THE HATCH  CAME LOOSE. AS THE DRIVER MADE MANDATORY STOPS AND NEGOTIATED TURNS, THE SURGE OF THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK SPLASHED OUT ONTO THE GROUND IN 4 DIFFERENT AREAS RANGING IN SIZE FROM 446 FEET TO 2196 FEET. THESE SPILLS WERE DISCOVERED BY THE RAILROAD TRACKS (MANDATORY STOPS) WHERE  THE SPILLS STARTED, TURNING ONTO CRAIG ROAD, TURNING OFF CRAIG ROAD TO COUNTRY ROAD 390. THE LAST SPILL WAS LOCATED ON THE MID STATE WELL LOCATION. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DOG EARS SECURING THE HATCH CAME LOOSE IN TRANSIT. WHEN THE UNIT STOPPED AT THE RAILROAD CROSSING, THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK CREATED A SURGE MOVING THE PRODUCT FORWARD IN THE TANK, AND AT THE TIME THE FORCE OF THE PRODUCT CONTAINED OT THE ROADWAYS ONLY. DUE TO DARKNESS, THE DRIVER WAS UNAWARE OF THE SPILLS UNTIL HE ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION. ASSISTANT FIRE MARSHAL WAS ON SCENE, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH HIM. THE UNIT, ONCE ON LOCATION WAS SECURED IN A CONTAINED AREA. A HAZMAT CLEANUP CREW WAS NOTIFIED ALONG WITH OKLAHOMA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. IT HAS BEEN ESTIMATED THAT 338 GALLONS OF PRODUCTS WAS SPILLED. THE TANKER CAPACITY WAS 5000 GALLONS AND THE PRODUCTS SHIPPED WAS 4778 GALLONS.
column169: IT HAS BEEN SUGGESTED THAT THE ORIGINAL LOAD OF TOTES COULD HAVE BEEN SENT DIRECTLY TO THE DESTINATION INSTEAD OF THE ORIGIN. TRAVEL WOULD HAVE BEEN SHORTER FOR THE FLATBED OF TOTES. IN ADDITION, THE TRANSFER OF MATERIAL WOULD HAVE TAKEN PLACE ON A SECURE LOCATION, AND NOT TRAVEL WOULD HAVE BEEN INVOLVED, THEREFORE ELIMINATING THE RISK. DOUBLE CHECKING DURING THE PRE-TRIP OF THE UNIT ITSELF. ALTHOUGH THE HATCH IN QUESTION WAS NEVER UTILIZED BY THIS DRIVER, HE SHOULD HAVE DOUBLE CHECKED THE DOG EARS ON THE FRONT HATCH. IT HAS BEEN SUGGESTED THAT A SEAL ASSIGNED TO THE DRIVER BE PLACED ON THE HATCH, AND FOR THAT SEAL TO BE VERIFIED AGAINST SEAL NUMBER ON PAPERWORK. THIS DOCUMENTATION ALERTS THE DRIVER IF THE HATCH HAS BEEN OPENED OR TAMPERED WITH.
